abstract: The yachts Cambria and Dauntless have started on their ocean race. abstract: GEOMORE H. POST, of Bergen, N. J., visited this City on Thursday last, and during the evening met KITTY HARRISON, who persuaded him to visit CHARLES SMITH'S liquor-saloon in Canal-street. Among the incidents of the turmoil we may chronicle the following. which will be but imperfectly verified in the then crude journals of the day.

abstract: About 2 o'clock P. M., yesterday, a branch sower now being excavated in the upper end of Broad-street, Newark, near the Morris and Essex Railroad Depot, caved in without warning, and buried two men out of sight. The sower was about twenty feet deep, was boarded up with spruce planking, braced by cedar cross pieces at intervals of about four feet.

abstract: The Philadelphia Telegraph, of July 29, says: Yesterday considerable correspondence took place between the proprietors of the Pennsylvania sugar Refinery, at Crown and, Race streets, recently destroyed by fire, and the Chief of Police, relative to the removal of the insecure walls of the ruins.

abstract: About two years ago there came to this city, from C-, a gentleman by the name of R-; a lovely wife and two beautiful children, a little boy and girl, aged four and six respectively, accompanied him. abstract: About 9 o'clock last evening another stormcloud passed over this vicinity, hovering overhead, however, just long enough to deluge the earth below with rain, and furnish another display of warring elements. The storm continued about halfan hour,but in that time caused damage which will require many months to repair.
